  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Pacing is the control of speed in writing — how quickly the reader moves through the text and how much time any given moment receives. Pacing operates at every scale: sentence, paragraph, section, and whole text.\nAt the sentence level, short sentences speed the reader up; long sentences slow them down. At the paragraph level, white space and section breaks create pauses. At the narrative level in fiction, the choice between scene and summary is the primary pacing tool: scene expands time (a five-minute conversation takes two pages), while summary compresses it (three years pass in a sentence).\n",
